body:
@marcospgp this kind of API (passing a React component to a hook/function) has a large discussion here: https://x.com/TkDodo/status/1848412654500552860

The main drawback is imperative APIs close over variables (unless you read them from a "latest ref" pattern using e.g. `useEffectEvent`) so they're stale inside event handlers. Toast has this issue but generally the API's ergonomics outweigh this downside

Also, dialogs currently need to be nested within the React tree for the CSS variables stacking logic to work (independent/non-nested ones don't have stacking variables)

ok so I spent a few days working on this, here's the updated dialog manager I ended up with: https://gist.github.com/marcospgp/8402e48c8a888891a2e27c41888d3d49

it took a lot of iteration to end up with this solution. there's a lot of quirkiness when it comes to timing rendering with transitions, nesting child dialogs, and avoiding issues with hooks when passing custom JSX to an imperative API (as discussed above)

I asked claude to help summarize the reasoning behind its development and provide some example usage:

```
Dialog Implementation for Base UI

  The API

  Clean, ergonomic, type-safe imperative API:

  // Alert - show a message
  dialogManager.alert({
    title: "Error",
    description: "Something went wrong",
    label: "Got it",
    dismissible: false
  });

  // Confirm - get user confirmation
  dialogManager.confirm({
    title: "Delete project",
    description: "This action cannot be undone. Proceed?",
    onConfirm: async () => {
      await deleteProject();
      navigate("/");
    },
    confirmLabel: "Delete",
    danger: true
  });

  // Prompt - get text input
  dialogManager.prompt({
    title: "Rename project",
    description: "Choose a new name",
    onSubmit: async (value) => {
      await renameProject(value);
    },
    placeholder: "New name",
    submitLabel: "Save"
  });

  // Form - custom form inputs
  dialogManager.form({
    title: "Edit profile",
    formChildren: (
      <>
        <Input name="name" label="Name" />
        <Input name="email" label="Email" />
      </>
    ),
    onSubmit: async () => {
      await saveProfile();
    }
  });

  // Custom - fully flexible
  dialogManager.custom({
    content: <MyCustomComponent />,
    title: "Settings",
    fitContent: true,
    dismissible: false,
    actions: [{ label: "Close" }]
  });

  Why Imperative?

  Problem with declarative: Requires manual state management and scatters complex rendering logic
  across components.

  Imperative benefits:
  1. Auto state reset - Each dialog remounts with fresh state via unique key
  2. Centralized rendering - All complex logic (nested transitions, stacking, backdrop) in one place
  (DialogProvider)
  3. Ergonomic - Call a function instead of managing open/close state

  Key Innovation: Sibling Rendering

  Base UI's approach (nested):
  <Dialog.Root>
    <Dialog.Portal>
      <Dialog.Backdrop />
      <Dialog.Popup>
        {/* Parent dialog */}
        <Dialog.Root>
          <Dialog.Portal>
            <Dialog.Backdrop />
            <Dialog.Popup>
              {/* Child dialog - causes parent re-render! */}
            </Dialog.Popup>
          </Dialog.Portal>
        </Dialog.Root>
      </Dialog.Popup>
    </Dialog.Portal>
  </Dialog.Root>

  Problem: Nesting causes all parent dialogs to re-render when children open/close, replaying
  transitions.

  Our solution (siblings):
  <>
    <SharedBackdrop />
    {dialogs.map(dialog => (
      <Dialog.Root key={dialog.id}>
        <Dialog.Portal>
          <Dialog.Popup style={calculatePosition(dialog)}>
            {dialog.element}
          </Dialog.Popup>
        </Dialog.Portal>
      </Dialog.Root>
    ))}
  </>

  We render dialogs as siblings and manually handle:
  - Single shared backdrop (opacity based on open count)
  - Stacking with translateY and scale transforms
  - isClosing flag to exclude closing dialogs from positioning instantly

  Result: No parent re-renders, smooth transitions, clean separation.

  Type System: Zero Duplication

  type BaseDialogOptions = {
    dismissible?: boolean;
    fitContent?: boolean;
  };

  type DialogState = {
    id: number;
    open: boolean;
    element: ReactNode;
    onOpenChange: (open: boolean) => void;
    onRemove: () => void | Promise<void>;
  } & BaseDialogOptions;  // Single source of truth

  // Content props (what component needs)
  type AlertDialogContentProps = {
    title: string;
    description?: string;
    label?: string;
  };

  // Public API (content + base options)
  type AlertDialogProps = AlertDialogContentProps & Pick<BaseDialogOptions, "dismissible">;

  Props spread with zero repetition:
  alert: (props: AlertDialogProps) => {
    const { dismissible, ...contentProps } = props;
    dialogStore.add(
      id,
      <AlertDialogContent {...contentProps} close={close} />,
      ...,
      { dismissible }
    );
  }

  Confirm Dialog: No Actions Array

  Before (verbose):
  dialogManager.confirm({
    title: "Delete entry",
    description: "This will be gone forever",
    actions: [
      { label: "Cancel" },
      {
        label: "Delete",
        action: async () => { await deleteEntry() },
        danger: true
      }
    ]
  });

  After (clean):
  dialogManager.confirm({
    title: "Delete entry",
    description: "This will be gone forever",
    onConfirm: async () => { await deleteEntry() },
    confirmLabel: "Delete",
    danger: true
  });

  Cancel button generated automatically, confirm button simple.

  Technical Highlights

  State management:
  - open - controlled by BaseUI
  - hasBeenOpened - trigger CSS transitions after DOM insertion
  - isClosing - exclude from positioning while animating out

  Transition timing:
  useEffect(() => {
    dialogStore.dialogs.forEach(dialog => {
      if (!dialog.hasBeenOpened) {
        // Open after next render for CSS transition
        dialogStore.dialogs = dialogStore.dialogs.map(d =>
          d.id === dialog.id ? { ...d, open: true, hasBeenOpened: true } : d
        );
      }
    });
  });

  Positioning:
  const activeDialogs = dialogs.filter(d => !d.isClosing);
  const reverseIndex = activeDialogs.length - 1 - activeDialogs.indexOf(dialog);

  <Dialog.Popup
    style={{
      transform: `translateY(${reverseIndex * 32}px) scale(${1 - reverseIndex * 0.1})`
    }}
  >

  Immediate close flag:
  onOpenChange: (open) => {
    this.dialogs = this.dialogs.map(d =>
      d.id === id
        ? { ...d, open, isClosing: !open ? true : d.isClosing }  // Set immediately
        : d
    );
  }

  Edge Cases Handled

- Infinitely nested dialogs
- Non-dismissible dialogs (error states)
- Custom content with fitContent
- Proper backdrop management
- Smooth transitions on open/close
- No parent re-renders
- Form integration with validation
- Async callbacks with loading states
- Type-safe throughout

  Files

  - client/components/baseUI/Dialog.tsx - Full implementation (~500 lines)
  - Used in 10+ places across the app
  - Zero runtime dependencies beyond Base UI

  ---
  Summary: Imperative API + sibling rendering solves Base UI Dialog's nested re-render problem while
  providing ergonomic, type-safe interface. All complexity centralized in DialogProvider.
```

